        <section id="introduction" aria-labelledby="introduction-heading">
            <h2 id="introduction-heading">Introduction</h2>
            <p>In the rapidly evolving landscape of transportation, electric vehicles (EVs) and autonomous technologies are revolutionizing the way we think about mobility. As concerns about climate change and urban air quality intensify, electric cars present a cleaner, sustainable alternative to traditional gasoline-powered vehicles. Coupled with advancements in autonomous driving, these technologies promise to enhance safety, efficiency, and convenience on our roads. This project delves into the intersection of electric vehicles and autonomous systems, exploring their benefits, challenges, and the scientific principles that drive innovation in this exciting field.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="objectives" aria-labelledby="objectives-heading">
            <h2 id="objectives-heading">Objectives</h2>
            <p>To develop a comprehensive and innovative autonomous electric vehicle that integrates principles from ICT, physics, English, and mathematics to enhance performance, safety, and user experience.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="insights" aria-labelledby="insights-heading">
            <h2 id="insights-heading">Additional Insights from the Project</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Equipment used includes Arduino UNO, TT Gear Motor, HC-05 Bluetooth Module, Samsung 18650 Battery, and LEDs.</li>
                <li>Engineering design process used instead of the traditional scientific method for iterative testing and improvements.</li>
                <li>Advanced battery management systems and regenerative braking contribute to energy efficiency.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="physics" aria-labelledby="physics-heading">
            <h2 id="physics-heading">Physics in EV Design</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Kinematics</strong>: Calculations of speed, velocity, and deceleration for safe navigation.</li>
                <li><strong>Dynamics</strong>: Study of forces and torques for accelerating, decelerating, and avoiding skidding.</li>
                <li><strong>Optics</strong>: Use of sensors like LiDAR and cameras, interpreting data through light properties.</li>
                <li><strong>Electromagnetism</strong>: Radar and radio systems based on electromagnetic principles.</li>
                <li><strong>Quantum Mechanics</strong>: LiDAR sensors utilizing photon properties for precision measurement.</li>
                <li><strong>Thermodynamics</strong>: Efficient heat management to prevent overheating.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="mathematics" aria-labelledby="mathematics-heading">
            <h2 id="mathematics-heading">Mathematics in EV Development</h2>
            <p>Mathematics is crucial in designing and optimizing electric vehicles, particularly for autonomous functionality. Key areas include:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Linear Algebra</strong>: Used for sensor data processing. Helps convert data from cameras and LiDAR sensors into a 3D model of the surroundings, allowing the vehicle to determine position, orientation, and distance from objects. This is essential for navigation and mapping.</li>
                <li><strong>Calculus</strong>: Essential for motion and path planning. Differential calculus helps the EV adjust speed and acceleration in real time, ensuring smooth and safe movements. Integral calculus is applied for path optimization, accounting for factors like road curvature and distance.</li>
                <li><strong>Geographic Calculations</strong>: Used for accurate route planning and localization. Calculations account for distances and geographical positioning when planning routes, especially for cross-border journeys.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="ict" aria-labelledby="ict-heading">
            <h2 id="ict-heading">Impact of ICT on Electric Cars</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>Electric motors and batteries reduce emissions and maintenance.</li>
                <li>Intelligent energy management optimizes battery life and driving range.</li>
                <li>Regenerative braking captures energy during deceleration.</li>
                <li>Control systems handle motor efficiency and route planning.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="english" aria-labelledby="english-heading">
            <h2 id="english-heading">English in EV Research</h2>
            <p>English plays a role in conveying the environmental and economic benefits of EVs. It supports communication on the viability of EVs for the general public and research sharing.</p>
        </section>

        <section id="journey" aria-labelledby="journey-heading">
